player.seasonOutlook: There was a point earlier this decade when it would have been unthinkable for Sabathia to get another contract from the Yankees, let alone two. However, after finishing last season with his lowest ERA since 2012, Sabathia returned to the Yankees on a second straight one-year deal. Sabathia doesn't stand out in any one fantasy category any longer, but the resources needed to acquire him are minimal and he is a good bet for 150 innings, a mark he has missed just twice in his career. Sabathia's spot in the rotation will not be as secure as in past years, and the Yankees may limit his times through the order in individual starts, but the skills are there for him to a viable fantasy option for at least one more season.

Having failed to crack the Nationals' big-league roster, Jackson exercised his opt-out clause May 31. He landed with the A's on a minor-league deal a week later and ultimately debuted for his 14th big-league organization June 25, tossing six innings of one-run ball against the Tigers with seven strikeouts. From that point on, pretty much everyone was waiting for the bottom to drop out, but it never did. He was able to stave off the regression monster, finishing with a 3.33 ERA despite peripherals which portended a high-4.00s mark. The right-hander managed just an 8.1 K-BB%. His .240 BABIP was way low for a pitcher with an above-average opponents' line-drive rate (23.8 percent) and a 36.9 percent hard-hit rate. Chances are that Jackson, now 35, will find his way back into a big-league rotation, but expect the baseball gods to collect their debt before long.

Velasquez's line-drive rate spiked to 31.0 percent over the final month of 2018, resulting in a 10.70 ERA over his final 17.2 innings. His four-seamer was knocked around in September, particularly in two starts -- including his final outing of the season -- in which his velocity was down. To Velasquez's credit, he was able to stay on the field outside of a brief trip to the DL after taking a comebacker off the forearm. Velasquez finished with a 16.2 K-BB%, which would have ranked top-30 had he logged enough innings to qualify, and his FIP checked in at 3.75. It was a strong season as a whole, but there is still a good deal of risk he ends up in the bullpen given his health history, a lack of secondary pitches and the Phillies' overall competitiveness.

Chavez transitioned back to the bullpen full-time in 2018 and proceeded to post the lowest ERA of his 11-year career, finishing with a 2.55 mark in 95.1 innings overall and a stellar 1.15 ERA in 39 frames following a midseason trade to the Cubs. Now back with the Rangers, he'll hope to be a stabilizing force on a staff full of unproven arms. Jose Leclerc will presumably open as the team's closer, but Chavez could be the next man up should Leclerc struggle or get injured. Most will probably just want to wait and see if that happens instead of rostering Chavez on draft day, as his 24.4 percent strikeout rate is not strong enough to make him a budget Josh Hader despite a similarly heavy workload. Age-related regression can't be counted out for the 35-year-old, either.

Straily beat the estimators for the third straight season, this time by almost a full run. His strikeout and walk rates both went in the wrong direction, with his K-BB rate falling from 14.3 percent to 9.1 percent. That would have tied Gio Gonzalez for the third-worst mark among qualified starters had Straily logged enough innings to qualify. He ultimately fell about 40 innings short after missing time due to forearm and oblique injuries. He allowed a .460 SLG and .360 wOBA to left-handed batters and had an equal amount of homer trouble at home and on the road -- that's what happens when a fly ball pitcher allows a 46.9 percent hard-hit rate. Straily is still only 30 and the Marlins are going to need him to chew up innings, but that's about the extent of his value. Even at home, he's a fairly significant risk to the ratios.

Rodney kicked off the 2018 season as the Twins' closer, converting 25 of his 31 save opportunities before being flipped to the A's in mid-August. Upon arriving in Oakland, the veteran reliever transitioned to a setup role, with Blake Treinen working as the closer. Despite moving to a more pitcher-friendly park, Rodney's numbers took a step back across the board with the A's, though the 41-year-old still finished the season with a combined 3.36 ERA and 9.8 K/9 in 64.1 innings between the two stops. Unsurprisingly, Rodney posted a BB/9 north of 4.1 for the fourth straight season, resulting in a bloated 1.46 WHIP. He notched seven holds with Oakland and figures to reprise his role as one of team's top setup men in 2019. An injury to Treinen could open the door for him to take over as the closer.
